\section{Problem 1 (20 points)}\label{problem-1-20-points}}

Suppose \(\boldsymbol{x} = (x_1,\dots, x_n )^T\) are independent and
identically distributed random variables with probability density
function (pdf) given by

\[ f(x_i|\theta) = \theta(1-x_i)^{\theta-1};\ \ 0\le x_i\le 1,\ 0<\theta<\infty,\ i=1,\dots,n \]

\hypertarget{part-b-5-points}{%
\subsubsection{Part b (5 points)}\label{part-b-5-points}}

Give the likelihood \(L(\theta|\boldsymbol{x})\) and log-likelihood
\(\ell(\theta|\boldsymbol{x})\) functions in this situation.

\[ L(\theta|\boldsymbol{x}) = \displaystyle \prod_{i=1}^{n} \theta(1-x_i)^{\theta-1}
= (\prod_{i=1}^{n} \theta) (\prod_{i=1}^{n} (1-x_i)^{\theta-1})
=\theta^n \cdot \prod_{i=1}^{n} (1-x_i)^{\theta-1} \]

And thus,

\[ \ell(\theta|\boldsymbol{x}) = \ln(L(\theta|\boldsymbol{x}))= \ln(\theta^n \cdot \prod_{i=1}^{n} (1-x_i)^{\theta-1}) = n\ln(\theta)+\ln(\prod_{i=1}^{n} (1-x_i)^{\theta-1}) \]

\[= n\ln(\theta)+\sum_{i=1}^{n} ({\theta-1})\ln(1-x_i) =n\ln(\theta) + ({\theta-1}) \cdot \sum_{i=1}^{n} \ln(1-x_i) \]

\#\#\# Part c (4 points)

Find the Maximum Likelihood Estimator (MLE) \(\hat{\theta}\) for
\(\theta\).
\[ \frac{d}{d\theta}\ell(\theta\|\boldsymbol{x}) = \frac{n}{\theta}+ \sum\_{i=1}\^{n} \ln(1-x_i)\]

\[ MLE : \frac{n}{\theta}+ \sum\_{i=1}\^{n} \ln(1-x_i) =0 \implies \hspace{1em} \hat\theta = \frac{-n}{\sum_{i=1}^{n} \ln(1-x_i)}\]

\hypertarget{part-d-2-points}{%
\subsubsection{Part d (2 points)}\label{part-d-2-points}}

Show that your estimator is in fact a maximum. That is, check the second
derivative of the log-likelihood.

\[\frac{d^2}{d\theta}\ell(\theta|\boldsymbol{x}) = \frac{-n}{\theta^2}\]

\textbf{Response:} As can be seen, for any given \(\theta\), the second
derivative of the log-likelihood function will be negative. The slope of
the first derivative is therefore decreasing and a maximum of \(\ell\)
occurs where \$\ell\prime \$crosses the \(y\)-axis.

\subsubsection{Part f (4 points)}\label{part-f-4-points}}

To get an idea of how variable the maximum likelihood estimator is in
this case, let's generate many samples of size 32 from this
distribution, which is a Beta distribution with parameters \(1\) and
\(\theta\). We can do this by using \texttt{rbeta(32,\ 1,\ 7.3)}.

Generate at least 10,000 samples this way, compute the MLE for each, and
then plot a histogram of the values using ggplot. On the plot somewhere,
indicate what the standard deviation in those estimates is.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]

\NormalTok{samples }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{( }\FunctionTok{matrix}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{nrow =} \DecValTok{10000}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{ncol =} \DecValTok{32}\NormalTok{) )}

\hypertarget{part-d-4-points}{%
\subsubsection{Part d (4 points)}\label{part-d-4-points}}

Conduct a deviance goodness-of-fit (GOF) test for a lack of fit here.
Type out the null and alternative hypotheses, report the test statistic,
give the p-value, and provide an interpretation.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{gof\_ship }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{pchisq}\NormalTok{(ship\_poisson}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{deviance, }
                   \AttributeTok{df =}\NormalTok{ ship\_poisson}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{df.residual,}
                   \AttributeTok{lower.tail =}\NormalTok{ F) }
\CommentTok{\#same as 1{-}pschisq() without lower.tail=FALSE arg}

\FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{format}\NormalTok{(gof\_ship, }\AttributeTok{scientific=}\NormalTok{F))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] "0.0000001542447"
\end{verbatim}

\textbf{Response:} We test the hypotheses :

\(H_0:\) The model is correctly specified

\(H_a:\) The model is not correctly specified

with a right-tailed \(\chi\)-squared test.

The sum of squared residual deviance \(77.45\) on 24 degrees of freedom
is relatively large.

The \(p\)-value \(=1.542 \times 10^{-7}\) of effectively \(0\) provides
strong evidence to reject the null hypothesis, thus there is evidence
that this model is not correctly specified.

\hypertarget{part-e-2-points}{%
\subsubsection{Part e (2 points)}\label{part-e-2-points}}

Is there evidence that this model has overdispersion? Explain.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# sum of squared Pearson residuals}
\NormalTok{poisson\_Pearson\_residuals }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{residuals}\NormalTok{(ship\_poisson, }\AttributeTok{type =} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}pearson\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{sum\_squared\_pearson }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{sum}\NormalTok{(poisson\_Pearson\_residuals}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}

\FunctionTok{cat}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Sum of squared Pearson residuals:"}\NormalTok{, sum\_squared\_pearson)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## Sum of squared Pearson residuals: 69.51051
\end{verbatim}

\textbf{Response:} The dispersion statistic
\(\frac{}{}=\frac{69.511}{24}=2.896\) is much greater than \(1.0\). This
suggests that the variance is much greater than the mean, contrary to
the essential property of the Poisson distribution. There may be
positive correlation between response probabilities and counts or too
much variation between response probabilities or counts. The standard
errors of estimates may be underestimated, leading to a false evaluation
of a model's precision.

\hypertarget{part-d-3-points}{%
\subsubsection{Part d (3 points)}\label{part-d-3-points}}

Fit a principal component model using the \texttt{pcr()} function in the
\texttt{pls} package. Since the variables are on very different scales,
use the \texttt{scale\ =\ TRUE} option in the function. Then find the
VIF values for this model. The \texttt{vif()} function from the
\texttt{car} library won't work here. Instead, take the diagonals of the
inverse of the correlation matrix (like we did in the regularization
section of Notes 7) for the \texttt{scores} output.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{pcr\_housing }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{pcr}\NormalTok{(medianValue }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{ . , }\AttributeTok{data=}\NormalTok{housing\_train , }\AttributeTok{scale=}\NormalTok{T)}


\NormalTok{vif\_scores }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ pcr\_housing}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{scores }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}} \FunctionTok{cor}\NormalTok{() }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}} \FunctionTok{solve}\NormalTok{() }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}} \FunctionTok{diag}\NormalTok{() }\SpecialCharTok{|\textgreater{}} \FunctionTok{round}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{)}

## Comp 8

\end{verbatim}

\textbf{Response:} All VIF scores are equal to 1, suggesting all
multicollinearity as been resolved, as expected, by principal components
of the regression.

\hypertarget{part-e-5-points}{%
\subsubsection{Part e (5 points)}\label{part-e-5-points}}

Now take the summary of your principal component model. With PCA, the
common amount of variation we want to explain in the predictors is 90\%
or more. How many components are needed to achieve this? For that number
of components, how much of the variation in log of home values is
explained? How many components are needed to explain a ``good'' amount
of the variation in the log of home values? Note: the upper bound on the
amount of variation in the log of home values here with all 8 components
will be equal to the \(R^2\) value of the OLS model.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{summary}\NormalTok{(pcr\_housing))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## Data:    X dimension: 16510 8 
##  Y dimension: 16510 1
## Fit method: svdpc
## Number of components considered: 8
## TRAINING: % variance explained
##              1 comps  2 comps  3 comps  4 comps
## X              48.88   72.745    86.46    96.94
## medianValue     1.77    2.434    26.54    49.16
##              5 comps  6 comps  7 comps  8 comps
## X              98.60    99.47    99.81    100.0
## medianValue    49.37    66.51    66.53     66.9
## NULL
\end{verbatim}

\textbf{Response:} Four principal components at least are necessary to
explain more than \(90%
\) variation in the predictors, at \(96.94%
\), for which only \(49.16%
\) of variation in the \(\ln(medianHomeValue)\) is explained. All eight
components explain \(66.9%
\) of the variation in \(\ln(medianHomeValue)\), although \(100%
\) of the predictor variation is explained.

output to the summary of the PCA model. Explain what the differences
are.

\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Response:} Whilst the amount of variation in predictors
explained by each of the principal components is lower for the PLS
regression, at each component there is a greater portion of variation
explained in the log of median housing price.

How many components are needed to balance a good amount of variation
explained in \(X\) and in \(y\) for the PLS model?

\textbf{Response:}. Four principal components explain \(91.5%
\) of variation in \(X\) and \(60.1%
\) of variation in \(y\) whereas another large jump in explained
variance of \(y\) happens for 5 principal components at \(66.6%
\). After this, there is very little improvement in explaining variance
in the outcome. \(5\) principal components provides a good balance.

\hypertarget{part-h-5-points}{%
\subsubsection{Part h (5 points)}\label{part-h-5-points}}

In part e, you said how many components were needed for the PCA. Using
that number of components, use the PCA and PLS models to find the root
MSE of the model when predicting the testing set. Note: the root MSE (or
residual standard error, also abbreviated RMSE) is found by taking the
square root of the sum of squared residuals divided by the residual
degrees of freedom, which is \(n-p\). Also, be aware that when you use
the \texttt{predict()} function on your model, it will give you
predictions for each number of components. You can access the
predictions for using 3 components, for example, by typing
\texttt{predict(pca\_model,\ test\_set){[},,3{]}}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{pca\_predictions }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{predict}\NormalTok{(pcr\_housing, housing\_test)[,,}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{]  }
\NormalTok{pls\_predictions }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{predict}\NormalTok{(housing\_pls, housing\_test)[,,}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{]  }

\NormalTok{pca\_residuals }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ housing\_test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{medianValue }\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ pca\_predictions}
\NormalTok{pls\_residuals }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ housing\_test}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{medianValue }\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ pls\_predictions}

\CommentTok{\# RMSE}
\NormalTok{n }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{nrow}\NormalTok{(housing\_test)  }

\NormalTok{rmse\_pca }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{( }\FunctionTok{sum}\NormalTok{(pca\_residuals}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{/}\NormalTok{ (n }\SpecialCharTok{{-}} \DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{) )}
\NormalTok{rmse\_pls }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{( }\FunctionTok{sum}\NormalTok{(pls\_residuals}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{/}\NormalTok{ (n }\SpecialCharTok{{-}} \DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{) )}

\FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(rmse\_pca)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] 0.398395
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(rmse\_pls)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
## [1] 0.3511393
\end{verbatim}

\textbf{Response:} The PCA model has \(RMSE=0.398\) when predicting the
testing set. The PLS model has a lower \(RMSE=0.351\) when predicting
the testing set.

Using that number of components, use the PCA and PLS models to find the
